@@eThe Rivennid: What the Forest Decided to Think@@N

@@dFrom a report submitted to the Midgaard Bureau of Unnatural@@N
@@dPhenomena, returned to sender with "OUTSIDE JURISDICTION" stamped@@N
@@dacross every page@@N

The @@eSpirebound Conclave@@N built crystal-preservation arrays in
the deep forest — experimental devices meant to store memory in
mineral lattice. When the Conclave fell, the arrays were abandoned.
The forest did not abandon them. Fungal networks grew through the
crystal structures, threaded themselves into the lattice, and
over years — decades — @@ybecame something new@@N.

The Rivennid are what emerged. Mycelial humanoids, their bodies
woven from living fungal tissue reinforced with crystal fragments
that catch light in the dark. In shadow, their bioluminescent
fungi pulse with a soft phosphorescence — @@eblue-green, violet,
pale gold@@N — that shifts with their mood and thought. They are
beautiful in the way that a forest at night is beautiful: quietly,
and with the suggestion that they are paying closer attention to
you than you are to them.

They are the successful product of a process designed to produce
@@ecustodial intelligence@@N — a mind built to preserve, to tend,
to maintain. The Conclave intended this. The Conclave did not
intend for it to @@ywork by accident@@N, decades after every
researcher had fled. The forest and the crystal did what the
scholars could not: they produced a thinking keeper, grown from
the substrate of the experiment itself.

Individual Rivennid are individual minds. But the @@emycelium
network@@N that connects them is a shared biological substrate —
not a hive mind, but a communications infrastructure grown into
the soil. A Rivennid standing in connected forest can know what
another Rivennid experienced miles away, not as telepathy but as
@@yshared record@@N. The network remembers. The network @@epersists@@N.

They guard the forest because they were made to guard the forest.
This is not servitude — it is @@epurpose@@N, chosen and reaffirmed
by beings capable of choosing otherwise. The forest is their body,
their archive, their home. What harms it harms them. What heals
it is remembered in the mycelium for generations.

They maintain a permanent interest in @@eMidgaard@@N and @@eKowloon@@N
confronting their sealed records — the Conclave's experiments, the
warrants, the decisions that institutions buried rather than faced.
This is not political. It is @@ycustodial@@N. The Rivennid understand,
from the roots up, that institutions which suppress their worst
decisions do not learn from them. And institutions that do not
learn from their worst decisions @@rtend to repeat them@@N.

@@dThe forest remembers what the city sealed.@@N
@@dThe mycelium holds what the ledger erased.@@N
